[codex] Study 4B
[codex] In this study, we replicated Study 4A using feedback about the gender, rather than race, of authors initially selected for a local library reading list. Prior to this study, we conducted a pretest (N = 550) rating 21 candidate attributes on importance for gender (see Appendix Section S4 for full details). The three comparison attributes used did not differ significantly from gender on rated importance. We also examined whether political ideology or party affiliation moderated the effect of gender feedback.
[codex] 
[codex] Methods
[codex] Participants. As pre-registered (https://osf.io/de3bu/), we recruited 1,000 participants through Prolific Academic to complete a 3-minute survey for $0.75 (50.7% women; 48.0% men; 1.1% non-binary; Mage = 43.00; 75.9% White, 10.8% Black, 4.8% Hispanic, 8.0% Asian).
[codex] 
[codex] Procedure. Participants imagined creating a winter fiction reading list for their local library and selected six authors from a list of 25 real authors, six of whom were women (24%). Each author was displayed with a photograph, name (e.g., Kurt Vonnegut), most notable work (e.g., Slaughterhouse-Five), that workΓÇÖs estimated all-time sales and time in print (e.g., 800K copies sold, in print 56 years), number of works authored (e.g., 14 books, 3 essays), and genre(s) (e.g., Science Fiction, Satire).
[codex] 
[codex] Participants were randomly assigned to one of two conditions. In the no gender feedback condition, participants received summary statistics about the percentage of authors they had selected who (1) wrote works spanning multiple genres, (2) had at least one book with 30 million or more copies sold, and/or (3) had works that remained in continuous print for over 50 years. In the gender feedback condition, participants always received feedback about the percentage of authors they had selected who were women, alongside two randomly drawn pieces from the no gender feedback list. After receiving feedback, participants selected a seventh and final author to recommend for the reading list from the original candidate set, where their prior selections were highlighted.
[codex] 
[codex] After making all decisions, participants completed internal (CronbachΓÇÖs ╬▒ = 0.93) and external (CronbachΓÇÖs ╬▒ = 0.89) motivation to respond without prejudice measures from Study 4A, adapted to focus on gender prejudice. We also measured political ideology using the 7-point ANES political ideology scale, centered at 4 (moderate), and party affiliation using an ANES party identification item, dummy coded with Republican as the reference category. See Materials Section: Study 4B in the Appendix for complete study materials.
[codex] 
[codex] Results
[codex] Initial selections featured women authors 25.3% of the time, with balance across conditions (p = .679; see Appendix Table S9). Following our pre-registration, we ran an OLS regression with robust standard errors predicting whether the seventh and final author a participant selected was a woman; the primary predictor was assignment to the gender feedback condition. Participants were significantly more likely to choose a woman author as their seventh and final selection in the gender feedback condition (41.48% chose a woman author) than in the no gender feedback condition (29.54% chose a woman author; B = 0.119, 95% CI = [0.060, 0.178], t(998) = 3.97, p < .001; Table S9, Model 1).
[codex] 
[codex] The effect of assignment to the gender feedback condition on subsequent selection of a woman author was significantly larger than the effects of assignment to receive descriptive feedback about each of the three comparison attributes (all pΓÇÖs Γëñ .003; see Table 2 for cross-study estimates and Wald tests, and Table S9, Models 5-8, for Study 4B regressions). Political ideology did not moderate the effect of gender feedback (B = -0.013, 95% CI = [-0.044, 0.018], t(996) = -0.80, p = .424). Party affiliation also did not moderate the effect of gender feedback (Democrat interaction: B = 0.019, 95% CI = [-0.125, 0.164], t(994) = 0.26, p = .792; Independent interaction: B = 0.067, 95% CI = [-0.085, 0.220], t(994) = 0.87, p = .387).
[codex] 
[codex] Mediation. Following our pre-registration, we tested each proposed mediator independently using a 10,000-sample bootstrapped mediation model and a Sobel test (Imai et al., 2010). First, the 95% bias-corrected CI for the indirect effect of internal motivation to respond without prejudice excluded zero (indirect effect = 0.064, 95% CI = [0.037, 0.094]), suggesting that participantsΓÇÖ internal motivation to respond without prejudice partially accounted for the effect of assignment to the gender feedback condition on the likelihood of selecting a woman as the final author. Using Imai et al.ΓÇÖs (2010) average causal mediation effect approach, we found that 53.9% of the effect under study occurred through mediation by participantsΓÇÖ internal motivation to respond without prejudice. Next, the 95% bias-corrected CI for the indirect effect of external motivation to respond without prejudice also excluded zero (indirect effect = 0.030, 95% CI = [0.014, 0.048]), suggesting that participantsΓÇÖ external motivation to respond without prejudice also accounted for the effect of assignment to the gender feedback condition on their likelihood of selecting a woman as their final author. Here, Imai et al.ΓÇÖs average causal mediation effect approach suggested that 24.8% of the effect under study occurred through mediation by participantsΓÇÖ external motivation to respond without prejudice.
[codex] 
[codex] Following our pre-registration, we next tested whether both internal and external motivation to respond without prejudice would continue to mediate the effect under study in a multiple mediation model, addressing the high correlation between these measures (r = 0.78, p < .001). The results confirmed that internal motivation to respond without prejudice significantly mediated the effect (indirect effect = 0.091, 95% CI = [0.052, 0.131]). When both mediators were included simultaneously, external motivation to respond without prejudice showed a significant negative indirect effect (indirect effect = -0.028, 95% CI = [-0.046, -0.012]).
